To implement AntDesign on the code for the "Log in with Google" button, you could replace the existing HTML and script with ReactJS components that use the `Button` component from AntDesign and the `GoogleOutlined` icon from `@ant-design/icons`. Here is the modified code:

```
import React, { useEffect } from 'react';
import { Button } from 'antd';
import { GoogleOutlined } from '@ant-design/icons';

function GoogleLoginButton({ clientId }) {
  useEffect(() => {
    const handleCredentialResponse = (response) => {
      console.log("Encoded JWT ID token: " + response.credential);
    }
    google.accounts.id.initialize({
      client_id: clientId,
      callback: handleCredentialResponse
    });
    google.accounts.id.prompt(); // also display the One Tap dialog
  }, [clientId]);

  return (
    <div id="buttonDiv">
      <Button icon={<GoogleOutlined />} size="large" onClick={google.accounts.id.prompt}>
        Log in with Google
      </Button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default GoogleLoginButton;
```

In this code, we define a `GoogleLoginButton` component that accepts a `clientId` prop. Inside this component, we use the `useEffect` hook to initialize the Google Sign-In API and handle the credential response, as in the original code. We then render a `Button` component with the Google icon and the text "Log in with Google". When the button is clicked, we call the `prompt` method of the Google Sign-In API to display the One Tap dialog.

To use this component, you can import it in another component and pass in your Google client ID as a prop:

```
import React from 'react';
import GoogleLoginButton from './GoogleLoginButton';

function MyComponent() {
  const clientId = "YOUR_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID";

  return (
    <div>
      <GoogleLoginButton clientId={clientId} />
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;
